Certainly! Writing a poem in LaTeX involves using the `poetry` environment or simply formatting the text manually. Below is an example of a short poem that expresses the sentiment of "laughing out loud," formatted using LaTeX:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{verse}

\begin{document}

\begin{verse}
\poemtitle{Laughing Out Loud}

In a world so vast, I find delight,\\
A spark ignites, a feeling so bright.\\
Laughter echoes through the air,\\
Joyful moments, beyond compare.\\

With every chuckle, worries fade,\\
A symphony of joy, sweetly played.\\
Let the world hear, let it be told,\\
The magic of laughter, untold, unfolds.\\
\end{verse}

\end{document}
```

This LaTeX code uses the `verse` package for poetry, which helps maintain the structure of the poem. Each line ends with `\\` to indicate a line break, and the poem's title is set using `\poemtitle{}`. You can compile this code with a LaTeX editor to see the formatted poem.
